pr_body:
Resolves #1854

This is most of the GSoC 2020 work by @adityaa30. There is additional work which will be handled in separate pull requests.

To do:

- [x] https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/pull/4769#issuecomment-697141375
- [x] https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/pull/4769#issuecomment-729635590
- [x] Document the (hard-coded) maximum frame size accepted from servers
- [x] Remove the logging of server-initiated request handling
- [x] Document that server-initiated requests are ignored
- [x] Add `Request.protocol` support (#4878) (done in e494a3f73318db76d7c56e65bc632cd5875b8825)
- [x] Document that the `bytes_received` signal is not implemented
- [x] Make tests pass
- [x] Improve coverage as much as possible before merging for Scrapy 2.5

After merging:
- [x] Create a [milestone for production-ready HTTP/2 support](https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/milestone/37), with the following issues:
    - [x] [Support the `bytes_received` signal](https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/issues/5046)
    - [x] [Successfully crawling 1 million popular domains in Zyte Scrapy Cloud](https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/issues/5047) (at the moment there are memory issues)
    - [x] [Handle the `dataloss` flag as in the HTTP/1.1 response handler](https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/issues/5048)
- Create additional issues to:
    - [x] [Implement complete code coverage for HTTP/2 code](https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/issues/5049)
    - [x] [Create a setting for the maximum frame size accepted from servers](https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/issues/5050)
    - [x] [Test handling of servers sending a non-UTF8 string as protocol](https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/issues/5051)

[{'comment_id': 581915152, 'comment_body': 'What about #4440? :smile: ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 2, 24, 12, 24, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'elacuesta', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 581919550, 'comment_body': 'That was triggered by [this comment by me](https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/pull/4054#discussion_r351514071) (emphasis added):

> We should not use assert statements in production code, outside tests, **where we know the assertion may fail**.

In this case, no input could ever make that `assert` raise an `AssertionError`. The code is written so that this condition will always be `True`. If that ever changes, the cause will be a bug in the code, not unexpected input.

*But*, if you prefer, we could just replace it with a comment besides the `else`. However, if we ever extend the possible values of `StreamCloseReason` and forget to update this part of the code accordingly, an `assert` could cause tests to fail; a comment could cause us to forge to update this code.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 2, 24, 12, 31, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Gallaecio', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 582158624, 'comment_body': 'Fair enough, thanks for the explanation :slightly_smiling_face: ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 2, 24, 17, 31, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'elacuesta', 'type': 'User'}]
